{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8f8134d2-4fd9-405c-bce9-27b0522cf7f4","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me help you directly.\n\nHere are the main tools for .NET crash dump analysis:\n\n### `dotnet-dump analyze`\n```bash\n# Install the tool\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-app.dmp\n\n# Useful commands inside the analyzer:\n> clrstack          # managed call stacks\n> pe                # print last exception\n> dumpheap -stat    # heap summary\n> eestack           # all thread stacks\n```\n\n### `lldb` (Linux)\n```bash\ndotnet symbol --dump your-app.dmp   # download symbols\nlldb --core your-app.dmp\n```\n\n### Visual Studio (Windows)\nOpen the `.dmp` file directly — it provides a rich UI for inspecting threads, exceptions, and memory.\n\n---\n\n**Quick triage steps:**\n1. Run `dotnet-dump analyze your.dmp`\n2. Use `pe` to print the exception that caused the crash\n3. Use `clrstack` to see the call stack of the faulting thread\n4. Use `setthread` + `clrstack` to inspect other threads if needed\n\nWould you like me to help you run `dotnet-dump analyze` on your dump file now? If so, share the path to the `.dmp` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e8c75aab-891a-4b73-a9f8-cc7c96d6c3a3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\". So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"D811:283A56:3556C3A:3A61777:69FBF16C"},"id":"09ab32eb-dfb4-48b0-98b8-64819d4336bb","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:57:15.706Z",